ork]]''</center>\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"|2009\n| [[Independent Spirit Awards]]\n| [[Independent Spirit Robert Altman Award|Robert Altman]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Tony Award]]\n| [[Tony Award for Best Actress in a Play|Best Actress in a Play]]\n| <center>''[[God of Carnage]]''</center>\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award]]\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Drama Series|Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Drama Series]]\n| <center>''[[In Treatment (U.S. TV series)|In Treatment]]''</center>\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 2010\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award]]\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Miniseries or a Movie|Outstanding Lead Actress in a Miniseries or a Movie]]\n| rowspan=3 |<center>''[[The Special Relationship (film)|The Special Relationship]]''</center>\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Satellite Award]]\n| [[Satellite Award for Best Actress \u2013 Miniseries or Television Film|Best Actress \u2013 Miniseries or Television Film]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2011\n| [[Golden Globe Award]]\n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actress \u2013 Series, Miniseries or Television Film|Best Supporting Actress \u2013 Series, Miniseries or Television Film]]\n|{{nom}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0204706}}\n* [http://www.emmys.com/celebrities/hope-davis Hope Davis at Emmys.com]\n\n{{New York Film  Critics Circle Award for Best Actress}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Davis, Hope}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Actresses from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American stage actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Englewood, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People from Tenafly, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Tenafly High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Vassar College alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American actress|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image      = Hope Davis 2010.jpg\n| caption    = Davis at the 2010 Peabody Awards\n| birthname  = \n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1964|3|23}}| birth_place = [[Englewood, New Jersey]], U.S.\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| occupation = Actress, Singer\n| othername  = \n| website    = \n| spouse     = {{marriage|Ford Evanson<br>|1989|1996|end=divorced}}<br>{{marriage|Jon Patrick Walker<br>|2000|}}\n| children   = 2\n| alma_mater = [[Vassar College]] (B.S., 1986)<ref name=\"VASSAR\">[http://vsa.vassar.edu/orgs/vice/2011/10/the-family-tree-screening-and-reception-with-writer-producer-mark-lisson/ \"\u201cTHE FAMILY TREE\u201d screening and reception with writer, producer MARK LISSON\"], Vassar College, October 2011</ref>\n}}\n'''Hope Davis''' (born March 23, 1964) is an American actress. She has starred in films such as ''[[About Schmidt]]'' (2002) and ''[[American Splendor (film)|American Splendor]]'' (2003). For her role in the original [[Broadway (theatre)|Broadway]] production of ''[[God of Carnage]]'' in 2009, she received a [[Tony Award]] nomination for [[Tony Award for Best Actress in a Play|Best Actress in a Play]]. She has also received two [[Emmy Award]] nominations, for her 2009 television roles in the series ''[[In Treatment (U.S. TV series)|In Treatment]]'' and in the film ''[[The Special Relationship (film)|The Special Relationship]]''. In 2016, she appeared in the [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]] film ''[[Captain America: Civil War]]'' as [[Iron Man|Tony Stark]]'s mother [[Maria Stark]].\n\n==Career==\n\n===Film===\nDavis made her debut as a dramatic actress in the 1990 film ''[[Flatliners]]'', starring as [[William Baldwin]]'s fianc\u00e9e. She then appeared in the hit film ''[[Home Alone]]'' in a small role as a Parisian airport receptionist. Later, she starred in independent films such as ''[[The Daytrippers]]'' ([[1995 in film|1995]]) and ''[[Next Stop Wonderland]]'' ([[1998 in film|1998]]). These led her to roles in Hollywood films such as the thriller ''[[Arlington Road]]'' ([[1999 in film|1999]]), and ''[[About Schmidt]]'' ([[2002 in film|2002]]). In 2003, she starred opposite [[Paul Giamatti]] in the movie adaptation of the [[Harvey Pekar]] comic ''[[American Splendor (film)|American Splendor]]'' as the comic book version of Pekar's real-life wife, [[Joyce Brabner]]. For this role, Davis won the New York Film Critics Circle award and was nominated for a Golden Globe for Best Actress in a Supporting Role. In 2009, she was cast as [[Hillary Clinton]] in the BBC / HBO film ''[[The Special Relationship (film)|The Special Relationship]]'', released in 2010.<ref>Andreeva, Nellie (8 July 2009). \"[http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/news/e3i4922fa0cb13ab3653dc7f0d387bf53f6?imw=Y Hope Davis to play Hillary Clinton]\". ''The Hollywood Reporter'' (Nielsen Business Media).</ref> She has received a nomination for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress \u2013 Miniseries or a Movie|Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress \u2013 Miniseries or a Movie]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emmys.com/celebrities/hope-davis |title=Hope Davis Emmy Nominated |publisher=Emmys.com |date= |accessdate=2012-08-17}}</ref> for her performance as Clinton. In 2015, she was approached by Marvel to play Maria Stark, mother of Tony Stark in Captain America: Civil War.\n\n===Stage===\nHer major stage debut came after she starred in the Wisdom Bridge/Remains Theater co-production of David Mamet's play ''[[Speed-the-Plow]]'' for [[Joel Schumacher]] (her \"Flatliners\" director) with [[William Petersen]] in Chicago in 1992. Later, she had lead roles in the New York premiere of Rebecca Gilman's ''[[Spinning into Butter]]'' in 2000, and in the 2005 audio play ''Hope Leaves the Theater'', written and directed by [[Charlie Kaufman]]. This was a segment of the sound-only production ''Theater of the New Ear'', which debuted at St. Ann's Warehouse in Brooklyn, NY. The title actually refers to Davis's character \"leaving the theater.\"\n\nShe returned to the stage in 2009, appearing in Broadway's ''[[God of Carnage]]'' with [[Marcia Gay Harden]], [[James Gandolfini]] and [[Jeff Daniels]],<ref>[https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5hJUlaeIU9r4lgCGrOgOyjQlbIbMAD95LP6QG0 Gandolfini Stars on Broadway in God of Carnage] The Associated Press, January 12, 2009</ref> a role that gained her a [[Tony Award]] nomination for [[Tony Award for Best Performance by a Leading Actress in a Play|Best Leading Actress in a Play]].\n\n===Television===\nDavis co-starred as the bitter and self-deprecating Mia with [[Golden Globe]] winner [[Gabriel Byrne]] in the second season (2009) of [[HBO]]'s ''[[In Treatment (U.S. TV series)|In Treatment]]'', a dramatic series that tracks the backstory and progress of five patients during their series of psychological therapeutic sessions. Mia is a successful, unmarried [[malpractice]] attorney who returns to therapy with Dr. Paul Weston after a 20-year absence because of a lack of stability in her personal life.\n\nDavis also starred in an [[NBC]] short-lived drama series called ''[[Deadline (2000 TV series)|Deadline]]'' with [[Oliver Platt]] in 2001. She played the ex-wife to Platt's character at a newspaper giant.\n\nDavis also starred in the short-lived NBC television drama, ''[[Allegiance (TV series)|Allegiance]]'', where she plays Katya O'Connor, an ex-[[KGB]] agent.  Her son works for the [[FBI]]/[[CIA]], and Katya's family is brought back into action by the [[Foreign Intelligence Service (Russia)|SVR]] in hopes that Alex, her son, can be swayed to join the SVR.\n\nShe later appeared in a reoccurring capacity on ''[[Wayward Pines]]'' and ''[[American Crime (TV series)|American Crime]]''.\n\nIn 2020, Davis narrated the [https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/nova/video/the-truth-about-fat/ The Truth About Fat] episode of the ''[[PBS]]'' television series ''[[Nova (American TV program)|Nova]]''.\n\n==Personal life==\nDavis, second of three children, was born in [[Englewood, New Jersey]], the daughter of Joan, a librarian, and William Davis, an engineer.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/382730361.html?dids=382730361:382730361&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&date=Aug+10%2C+2003&author=Robert+Abele&pub=Los+Angeles+Times&desc=Less+is+really+more%3B+Actress+Hope+Davis+prefers+to+make+her+mark+in+low-budget+enterprises+like+'The+Secret+Lives+of+Dentists'+and+'American+Splendor.'&pqatl=google |title=Less is really more; Actress Hope Davis prefers to make her mark in low-budget enterprises like 'The Secret Lives of Dentists' and 'American Splendor.' |work=Los Angeles Times |first=Robert |last=Abele |date=Aug 10, 2003}}</ref> Davis has described her mother as a \"great storyteller\" who would take Davis and her siblings to [[museum]]s or to \"something cultural\" every Sunday after church.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pbs.org/kcet/tavissmiley/archive/200509/20050926_davis.html |author=interview by Tavis Smiley |title=Hope Davis |date=September 26, 2005 |work=PBS}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=990CE7D91F3DF933A1575BC0A963958260&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=print |work=New York Times |date=August 20, 1995 |title=THEATER; The Fine Edge Between a Role And Real Life |first=BRUCE |last=WEBER}}</ref> Davis was raised in [[Tenafly, New Jersey]] and graduated in 1982 from [[Tenafly High School]].<ref>Kennedy, Dana. [https://www.nytimes.com/1998/09/13/movies/new-season-film-up-coming-hope-davis-lucky-for-her-she-flunked-nuprin-audition.html \"THE NEW SEASON/FILM: UP AND COMING: Hope Davis; Lucky for Her, She Flunked the 'Nuprin' Audition\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', September 13, 1998. Accessed December 18, 2013. \"Ms. Davis, who grew up in Tenafly, N.J., where she was the second of three daughters, has no explanation for her long, lean period other than to say, 'I just wasn't ready for success.'\"</ref><ref>Rohan, Virginia. [http://www.northjersey.com/page.php?qstr=eXJpcnk3ZjczN2Y3dnFlZUVFeXkxOTMmZmdiZWw3Zjd2cWVlRUV5eTcxNTE5NDcmeXJpcnk3ZjcxN2Y3dnFlZUVFeXk3 \" North Jersey-bred and talented too\"]{{dead link|date=April 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, ''[[The Record (Bergen County)]]'', June 18, 2007. Accessed July 5, 2007. \"Hope Davis: Class of 1982, Tenafly High School.\"</ref> She was a childhood friend of [[Mira Sorvino]], who lived almost directly across the street, and with whom she wrote and acted in backyard plays. Davis graduated from [[Vassar College]] with a degree in [[cognitive science]]. She studied acting at [[HB Studio]] in New York City.<ref>[https://hbstudio.org/about-hb-studio/alumni/ HB Studio Alumni]</ref> She is married to actor Jon Patrick Walker. They have two daughters, Georgia (born August 31, 2002) and Mae (born December 30, 2004).\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|1990\n|''[[Flatliners]]''\n|Anne Coldren\n|\n|-\n|1990\n|''[[Home Alone]]''\n|French Ticket Agent\n|\n|-\n|1995\n|''Run for Cover''\n|Prescott's Secretary\n|\n|-\n|1995\n|''[[Kiss of Death (1995 film)|Kiss of Death]]''\n|Junior's Girlfriend\n|\n|-\n|1996\n|''{{sortname|The|Daytrippers}}''\n|Eliza Malone D'Amico\n|\n|-\n|1996\n|''[[Mr. Wrong]]''\n|Annie\n|\n|-\n|1997\n|''{{sortname|The|Myth of Fingerprints}}''\n|Margaret\n|\n|-\n|1997\n|''[[Guy (1997 film)|Guy]]''\n|Camera\n|\n|-\n|1998\n|''[[Next Stop Wonderland]]''\n|Erin Castleton\n|\n|-\n|1998\n|''{{sortname|The|Impostors}}''\n|Emily Essendine\n|\n|-\n|1999\n|''[[Arlington Road]]''\n|Brooke Wolfe\n|\n|-\n|1999\n|''[[Mumford (film)|Mumford]]''\n|Sofie Crisp\n|\n|-\n|2000\n|''[[Joe Gould's Secret (film)|Joe Gould's Secret]]''\n|Therese Mitchell\n|\n|-\n|2001\n|''[[Final (film)|Final]]''\n|Dr. Ann Johnson\n|\n|-\n|2001\n|''[[Hearts in Atlantis (film)|Hearts in Atlantis]]''\n|Liz Garfield\n|\n|-\n|2002\n|''[[About Schmidt]]